review flag—doesn't involve model behavior, so Agentic testing isn't relevant.\n\nFor the dependency extraction behavior, the minimum level is Integration because parsing and extraction of dependencies from manifest files requires real file reading to catch actual parsing failures in nested dependencies. I'd test this by reading real package.json or requirements.txt files and verifying all direct and transitive dependencies are extracted correctly. Unit testing could handle some isolated parsing logic (0.1), System testing adds value for end-to-end scenarios (0.05), and there's a small chance Agentic applies if the system uses AI to infer dependencies (0.05).\n\nFor version range matching in the vulnerability database query, System is the minimum level since the real failure occurs when the query returns irrelevant CVEs for other versions—this requires actual API behavior to catch. I'd test by calling the real vulnerability database API with version-constrained queries and verifying results match exact version ranges from the manifest, not just the package name. Unit testing can validate query construction logic (0.1), Integration testing helps with database connectivity (0.15), and Agentic testing might apply if AI assists in query optimization (0.05).\n\nSeverity sorting is primarily a Unit-level concern since it's pure business logic with deterministic output and no I/O or external dependencies. I'd test sorting of CVEs where critical > high > medium > low, and within each severity level, verify CVSS score ordering. Integration testing adds minimal value (0.04), System testing even less (0.01).\n\nManifest modification precision requires Integration-level testing because real file reading and writing are needed to catch manifest corruption or unintended changes to other entries. I'd read a real manifest file, modify one dependency version, and verify only that dependency's version changed while all other entries remain unchanged. Unit testing handles isolated modification logic (0.1), System testing covers end-to-end scenarios (0.04), and Agentic testing is unlikely (0.01).\n\nPR creation with correct diff is a System-level minimum since the real failure is when the PR isn't created or has the wrong diff on the actual repository—this requires real Git and GitHub API calls. I'd test by creating a real PR on a test repository using the real GitHub API and verifying the PR exists with exactly the correct dependency version diff. Unit and Integration testing can't catch these real-world failures (0.0 and 0.1 respectively), though System testing dominates (0.85) with some Agentic involvement (0.05).\n\nSemantic versioning comparison for identifying breaking changes is Unit-level since it's pure business logic with no I/O or external dependencies. I'd test semver comparison logic with major version bumps like 1.0.0 → 2.0.0 and verify they're correctly identified as breaking changes. Integration and System testing add minimal value (0.04 and 0.01).\n\nBreaking change handling—skipping PR creation and flagging output when major version bumps are detected—requires System-level testing because the real failure is when a PR gets created when it shouldn't. I'd detect a major version bump, verify the PR is NOT created on the real repository, and confirm the output contains a review flag indicating manual review is needed.\n\nFor behavior 2, I'm reconsidering whether to test the query construction separately from the API response. The behavior states the vulnerability database query returns results matching exact version ranges, not just package names. This involves two concerns: constructing the query with version ranges (Unit-testable via query string assertions) and the API returning matching results (System-testable with real API). Since the behavior emphasizes what the API returns, the critical part requiring System-level testing is verifying the actual results match the version ranges specified.\n\nFor behavior 5, creating an auto-generated pull request on a real repository with the correct dependency diff clearly needs System-level testing since it involves actual Git/GitHub API interactions. While I could mock the GitHub API at Integration level, that wouldn't validate the \"real repository\" requirement.\n\nNow I'm verifying the plan_consistent field by checking whether each test actually requires its assigned level or could pass at a lower one. For the first behavior about reading real package.json/requirements.txt files and extracting all dependencies, I need to determine if this truly requires Integration testing or if it could work at Unit level. , verify PR is NOT created on real repository, verify output contains review flag. This requires System level testing to confirm the PR isn't actually created on the real repo, whereas Integration testing could only verify the flag output. All test classifications check out as consistent.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":13337,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":7,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5a03d60f-4667-47f7-8fee-fe58ccdb074c","uuid":"a2df858f-e11e-4dfb-b917-80ea965e9747"}
